body:
This is my process for things like this in JProfiler. Other profilers might be different but the process is probably similar.

What I first to is add an object with some functions that I can insert to act as my trigger point. For example:

```scala
object Trigger() {
  def start(): Unit = println("Start trigger")
  def stop(): Unit = println("Start trigger")
}
```

Then right after a DataProcessor is created and where all compile time references should no longer be accessable, I would add a call to this function, e.g.

```scala
Trigger.start()
```

Then I would run this in a JProfiler configured with a "Method Invocation" Trigger on the `Trigger.start()`. The Action for the trigger would be "trigger heap dump", so we get a heap dump when this Trigger.start method is called. In JProfiler, this action can be configured to perform a full garbage collection. When that checked, in theory compile time objects should have all been garbage collected and won't appear in the heap dump. If they do, you should be able to examine the heap dump and find where those references still exist.
